AFRICAN SWINE FEVER IN CONGO (DEM. REP. OF THE ~)
Suspected outbreak
Emergency report
Translation of information received on 22 Apr 2003 from Dr Mabela
N'Lemba, Director Head of Department, Directorate for Animal
Production and Health (DPSA), Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and
Livestock, Kinshasa:
Report date: 18 Apr 2003.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and post-mortem.
From November 2002 to February 2003, a high mortality rate was
observed in pigs in 15 farms situated in the Province of Lower Congo,
especially in the harbour city of Matadi (in the western part of the
country).
Outbreaks:
Location: Province of Lower Congo
No. of outbreaks: ...
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
species / susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
sui / 461 /... / >80 percent / .... / .....
A mission conducted by PACE-RDC (1) and accompanied by two
technicians from the Kinshasa Veterinary Laboratory was sent to
investigate in situ from 11 to 16 Apr 2003.
Clinical signs:
- fever,
- loss of appetite for 2 to 3 days,
- reddening of the skin (especially in the area of the ears and the abdomen),
- superficial and increased breathing,
- diarrhoea.
In general, death is observed within 2 or 3 days after the appearance
of these clinical signs.
Post-mortem signs:
- splenomegaly with dark colouring,
- haemorrhages in the mesenteric nodes,
- petechiae in kidneys,
- digestive mucosa sprinkled with petechiae and serosity.
Samples were taken on the premises (from animals that survived the
disease) and in the public slaughterhouse of Matadi and were sent for
examination to the Kinshasa Veterinary Laboratory.
(1) PACE-RDC: Pan-African Programme for the Control of Epizootics -
Democratic Republic of the Congo
